And having smelled blood, they’ll sure come! It’s a question of when, not if.
Other than the referendum campaigns, the toughest political battles in Kenya this year are likely to be fought over IEBC.
Concerns about partisanship or sloppiness by the elections referee won’t be limited to its critics in the opposition, though.
Anyone who cares about free, fair and peaceful elections in Kenya in 2022 needs to call the commission out.
The bungling of the last presidential election by the IEBC was blamed for the nullification of its outcome by the Supreme Court and the tensions that engulfed the country in the months after that decision.
The judges criticised the IEBC for sloppiness, noting that the commission didn’t have all the vote tallying forms when they announced the results and that some forms lacked security features such as watermarks, signatures or serial numbers.
To inspire public confidence that it will perform better in 2022, the agency needs to prove it can get things right this time around.
There is zero chance it will win the much-needed public confidence by getting a simple tweet about the BBI wrong or showing outright partisanship. Or what do they smoke over there?
